	•	The contract reverts if not enough ETH is provided.
	2.	Bonding Curve Price Calculation
	•	Calculate baseCost = Cost(x).
	•	Calculate feeAmount = baseCost * 5%.
	•	Verify the user’s msg.value >= baseCost + feeAmount. Refund any excess ETH if needed.
	3.	Fee Transfer
	•	Immediately send feeAmount to feeRecipient.
	4.	Token Transfer to Buyer
	•	The contract transfers x tokens (plus any fraction) from its own balance to the buyer.
	5.	Update N
	•	N += x.
	6.	Uniswap Liquidity Management (Optional if you prefer it in the same transaction)
	1.	Take a portion (say 50%) of the baseCost or the leftover ETH after paying fees.
	2.	Swap half of it to WBTC.
	3.	Increase (or create) a liquidity position around ±5% ticks from the current ETH/WBTC price.
	4.	If we need to “re-center” fully, we might remove the old position first, then create a new position.
	7.	Emit Event
	•	event TokensBought(address indexed buyer, uint256 amountTokens, uint256 costETH);

5. Sell Workflow
	1.	User Calls sell(xTokens)
	•	The user must have approved xTokens for the BondingCurveSale contract to spend.
	2.	Bonding Curve Payout Calculation
	•	basePayout = Payout(x).
	•	feeAmount = basePayout * 10%.
	•	finalPayout = basePayout - feeAmount.
	3.	Fee Transfer
	•	The contract sends feeAmount to feeRecipient.
	4.	Token Transfer from Seller
	•	The contract pulls x tokens from the seller’s balance into the contract.
	5.	Update N
	•	N -= x.
	6.	Uniswap Liquidity Removal
	•	Remove enough liquidity to obtain finalPayout in ETH (we might remove more if needed to re-center).
	•	Swap the removed WBTC portion back to ETH.
	•	Sum up the ETH from the removal + contract’s existing ETH.
	•	Pay finalPayout to the seller.
	7.	Optional Re-Center
	•	If the plan is to re-center on every sell, remove the entire position, recalculate new ticks, then add the position again around ±5%.
	•	If we only do partial removal, we simply adjust the existing position.
	8.	Emit Event
	•	event TokensSold(address indexed seller, uint256 amountTokens, uint256 payoutETH);

6. Uniswap (v3-like) Liquidity Management

Below is a simplified approach (the actual code will use Uniswap’s NonfungiblePositionManager interface calls):
	1.	Determining Current Price
	•	We can query the ETH/WBTC pool for the current sqrtPriceX96.
	•	Convert that to a real price ratio (WBTC per 1 ETH or vice versa).
	2.	Calculating Tick Range (±5%)
	•	Let currentTick = the tick from the sqrtPrice.
	•	±5% in price corresponds to ± a certain number of ticks. (We can approximate ticks for a 5% range. For example, if 1 tick ~ 0.0001% price change, we can compute the offset in ticks.)
	3.	Position Creation or Increase
	•	Approve WBTC + ETH to the position manager.
	•	Call mint(...) or increaseLiquidity(...) with the chosen tickLower and tickUpper.
	•	If it’s a new position, store the tokenId. If it’s an existing position, we use tokenId to increase liquidity.
	4.	Position Removal
	•	Call decreaseLiquidity(...) and collect(...) on the existing tokenId.
	•	Convert the collected WBTC to ETH if needed (via a swap in the Uniswap router).
	5.	Re-Center
	•	We typically must:
	•	Remove liquidity from the old range.
	•	Immediately re-add in a fresh range around the new price.

Because Uniswap v4 is still conceptual, we’ll assume the interface and approach is very similar to v3’s INonfungiblePositionManager.

7. Fees & Distribution

Each transaction collects fees:
	•	5% on Buys
	•	Immediately deducted from the user’s ETH payment.
	•	Sent to feeRecipient.
	•	10% on Sells
	•	Deducted from the user’s final payout.
	•	Immediately sent to feeRecipient.

(Optionally, you can store them in the contract and have an admin function to withdraw them in batches. But from your clarifications, immediate distribution is simpler.)

8. Security & Access
	•	Ownership/Administration
	•	The contract will have an owner who can:
	•	Change feeRecipient.
	•	Change the base price (basePrice) if needed.
	•	Change the ±5% range or the logic for re-centering (e.g., if 5% becomes 10%).
	•	Withdraw any leftover WBTC/ETH from the contract if no longer needed.
	•	ReentrancyGuard
	•	Each buy/sell function will use a nonReentrant modifier from OpenZeppelin to prevent malicious calls.
	•	Safe Transfers
	•	Use SafeERC20 from OpenZeppelin for token transfers.
	•	Use Address.sendValue or call.value with checks for ETH transfers.
	•	Bounds & Edge Cases
	•	Ensure the contract doesn’t sell more tokens than it holds (check contractTokenBalance >= x).
	•	If N becomes very large, exponentiation (1.01)^N might be huge. We’ll implement fixed-point exponentiation with checks for overflow.

9. Putting It All Together

High-Level Flow
	1.	Deployment
	•	Deploy BondingCurveSale with parameters: tokenAddress, basePrice, feeRecipient, positionManager, etc.
	•	Transfer up to 1 billion tokens from your project wallet to the sale contract.
	2.	Buying
	•	The user calls buy(x), sending enough ETH.
	•	The contract calculates cost, collects fees, updates the bonding curve, sends the tokens, re-centers Uniswap liquidity if desired.
	3.	Selling
	•	The user calls sell(x), approving x tokens first.
	•	The contract calculates payout, sends fees, updates the bonding curve, removes some or all Uniswap liquidity, and pays the user in ETH.
	4.	Liquidity Position
	•	The contract manages a single position (or multiple positions if needed) in the ETH/WBTC pool, re-centering around ±5% each time.
	5.	Fee Handling
	•	Instantaneous distribution to feeRecipient on each transaction.

10. Final Notes & Next Steps
	1.	Math Library: We’ll create or integrate a small library for:
	•	Exponentiation with base 1.01 in fixed-point arithmetic.
	•	Closed-form sum for buy/sell with partial tokens.
	2.	Gas Optimization:
	•	Because you’re on a cheaper L2 (Base), frequent re-centering is feasible, but we’ll still be mindful of excessive memory or loops.
	•	We’ll rely on the closed-form formula to avoid big loops for large x.
	3.	Upgradeability:
	•	If you want future changes without redeployment, we can incorporate OpenZeppelin’s Proxy pattern.
	•	Otherwise, we’ll keep it a simple, non-upgradeable contract.
	4.	Audits & Testing:
	•	For production, you’ll want thorough testing (e.g., hardhat or Foundry tests) and a security audit.

